<a class='reflink' href='../1.gis/1.3.tg.html#exampleequivalencerelationisnotetalewithproducttopology'>1.3.9</a>
<!-- 1.3.9 -->
<div class='toload example'>
	<p><span class='envidentifier'>Example 1.3.9</span>
	Let $R$ be an equivalence relation on a topological space $(X,\nu)$.
	</p>

	<p>
	In general, the product topology makes $R$ a non-étale topological groupoid, the simplest example being $R=X\times X$ when $X$ has any non-isolated point (see Proposition <span class='ref' data-tag='propositionetalehasbasisofbisections'></span>).
	</p>

	<p>
	On the other hand, suppose that $(X,\nu)$ is Hausdorff and $\tau$ is any topology on $R$ for which:
	<ol class='roman'>
		<li> $(R,\nu)$ is a compact étale topological groupoid;</li>
		<li> The range map $\ra:(R,\tau)\to(X,\nu)$ is continuous.</li>
	</ol>
	Then $\tau$ is induced from the product topology of $(X,\nu)\times(X,\nu)$ (see [<span class='ref' data-tag='MR2054051'></span>, Proposition 3.2]). In particular, in this case the topology $\nu$ of $X$, identified with $R^{(0)}$, is induced from $\tau$. (Compare this with Example <span class='ref' data-tag='exampleborelstructureequivalencerelationisunique'></span> in the Borel setting.)
	</p>
</div>